  - heading: Unit Testing in Unity
    text: 'Unity includes the Unity Test Framework (UTF), an NUnit-based
      harness for writing automated tests against your code. Tests live in
      their own assemblies and are executed from the Test Runner window
      (Window > General > Test Runner).<br><br>Tests fall into two categories:
      Edit Mode tests, which run synchronously inside the editor without
      entering Play Mode, and Play Mode tests, which run inside Unity''s
      runtime with frame-by-frame execution, physics, and MonoBehaviour
      lifecycle methods active.<br><br>See EditModeTestExamples.cs and
      PlayModeTestIntro.cs in the _Scripts folder for worked examples of
      each.'
    linkText: Unity Test Framework Manual
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.test-framework@1.4/manual/index.html
  - heading: Edit Mode vs. Play Mode Tests
    text: Prefer Edit Mode tests whenever the code under test is pure C#
      logic — constructors, algorithms, data transformations, state machines.
      Edit Mode tests run in milliseconds, are easy to isolate, and produce
      clear failure output. Reach for Play Mode tests only when you
      genuinely need Unity''s runtime behavior, such as physics collisions,
      coroutines, frame-dependent logic, or MonoBehaviour lifecycle timing.
      Play Mode tests are slower, harder to isolate, and more difficult to
      debug, so the cost of adding one should be justified by a real need
      for the runtime.
    linkText: Comparing Edit Mode and Play Mode Tests
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.test-framework@1.4/manual/edit-mode-vs-play-mode-tests.html
  - heading: Running Tests in the Test Runner
    text: Open the Test Runner via Window > General > Test Runner. The
      EditMode and PlayMode tabs show their respective test suites. The
      first time you add tests, create a test assembly folder via
      Assets > Create > Testing > Tests Assembly Folder — this generates
      a correctly-wired assembly definition file for your tests. This has 
      been done in this project to avoid compiler errors. A green
      check indicates a passing test; a red X indicates a failure, with
      expected vs. actual values shown in the details pane.
    linkText: Running Tests
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.test-framework@1.4/manual/workflow-run-test.html
  - heading: Assembly Definitions
    text: An Assembly Definition (.asmdef) file tells Unity to compile
      a folder's scripts into their own .NET assembly rather than the
      default Assembly-CSharp. This matters extra for tests because the Unity
      Test Framework only discovers tests inside an assembly that
      references the NUnit library and the test runner assemblies. Without
      an .asmdef, test scripts compile into Assembly-CSharp, and the Test
      Runner window will not find them.<br><br>The .asmdef files in this
      lesson's Tests folder (CPSC386.Tests.PlayMode.asmdef and
      CPSC 386.Tests.EditMode.asmdef) are configured for
      both Edit Mode and Play Mode tests. Note the differences in their
      configurations.
    linkText: Assembly Definitions Reference
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/ScriptCompilationAssemblyDefinitionFiles.html
  - heading: Expected Sequence for Running These Tests
    text: 1. Open the project in Unity and let the editor finish
      importing. The CPSC386.Tests assemblies will compile as part of the
      normal import process.<br>2. Open the Test Runner via Window >
      General > Test Runner.<br>3. Select the EditMode tab. You should
      see six tests listed under CPSC386.Tests.EditModeTestExamples. Two
      of them are designed to fail on purpose — a red X is the expected
      result, not a broken setup.<br>4. Select the PlayMode tab. You
      should see one test under CPSC386.Tests.PlayModeTestIntro. Running
      it will cause Unity to briefly enter Play Mode, run the test, and
      exit.<br>5. Click Run All to execute everything, or select an
      individual test and click Run Selected. Failure details appear in
      the pane at the bottom of the Test Runner window.<br><br>If no
      tests appear, check that the .asmdef file is present in the
      _Scripts folder and that the Unity console shows no compilation
      errors. A missing reference to nunit.framework.dll is the most
      common cause of "zero tests discovered."
    linkText: Test Runner Workflow
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.test-framework@1.4/manual/workflow-run-test.html
  loadedLayout: 0
